entities.urls: [{"start": 256, "end": 279, "url": "https://t.co/G3vu6U9FkN", "expanded_url": "https://www.digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHistory", "display_url": "digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHist\u2026", "images": [{"url": "https://pbs.twimg.com/news_img/1597322322679304192/pfUcrk5S?format=jpg&name=orig", "width": 412, "height": 600}, {"url": "https://pbs.twimg.com/news_img/1597322322679304192/pfUcrk5S?format=jpg&name=150x150", "width": 150, "height": 150}], "status": 200, "title": "LGB and/or T History - Digital Transgender Archive", "description": "Any line we might try to draw to separate lesbian/gay/bisexual history (LGB) from transgender history (trans) would be imprecise, blurry, and certainly not straight. Because of the incomplete archives we have, attempts to separate histories of sexuality and gender transgression often resort to pure guesswork. Worse, just trying to find that line forces us to consider all of history through two modern categories \u2013 gender and sexuality \u2013 making it harder to understand the very thing we are researching.", "unwound_url": "https://www.digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHistory"}]

Worse, just trying to find that line forces us to consider all of history through two modern categories \u2013 gender and sexuality \u2013 making it harder to understand the very thing we are researching.", "unwound_url": "https://www.digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHistory"}]

You are invited to join a webinar: Archival Justice and Digital Collaborative Scholarship. After registering, you will receive a confirmation email about joining the webinar.", "description": "The main idea of the panel is to explore the role of archives in addressing past and contemporary inequalities of communities marginalized in official historiographies. In fact, we seek to critically explore the concept of archival justice within a transnational and diasporic perspective. This is, we hope to better understand the strategies, actions, resources and counternarratives that focus deeper and from multi-disciplinary perspectives seeking redress in forms of representation of Indigenous Peoples and afro-descendant communities in Latin America and the Caribbean. What are these initiatives are telling us about justice and memory? What are the barriers these initiatives confront in the work they do? What alliances and collaboration are deemed necessary?", "unwound_url": "https://yorku.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_Iyl17gXLSY-X-poCSsEuSw"}, {"start": 187, "end": 210, "url": "https://t.co/8qbISLZGL7", "expanded_url": "https://twitter.com/CERLACYorkU/status/1597616582653808640/photo/1", "display_url": "pic.twitter.com/8qbISLZGL7", "media_key": "3_1597616051231117313"}]

entities.urls: [{"start": 256, "end": 279, "url": "https://t.co/G3vu6U9FkN", "expanded_url": "https://www.digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHistory", "display_url": "digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHist\u2026", "images": [{"url": "https://pbs.twimg.com/news_img/1597322322679304192/pfUcrk5S?format=jpg&name=orig", "width": 412, "height": 600}, {"url": "https://pbs.twimg.com/news_img/1597322322679304192/pfUcrk5S?format=jpg&name=150x150", "width": 150, "height": 150}], "status": 200, "title": "LGB and/or T History - Digital Transgender Archive", "description": "Any line we might try to draw to separate lesbian/gay/bisexual history (LGB) from transgender history (trans) would be imprecise, blurry, and certainly not straight. Because of the incomplete archives we have, attempts to separate histories of sexuality and gender transgression often resort to pure guesswork. Worse, just trying to find that line forces us to consider all of history through two modern categories \u2013 gender and sexuality \u2013 making it harder to understand the very thing we are researching.", "unwound_url": "https://www.digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHistory"}]

text: It is impossible to separate gay history from trans history, & attempts to do so inevitably collapse into bad scholarship. This has been a theme in my work for decades, and I'm honored that the Digital Transgender Archive invited me to write about it: https://t.co/G3vu6U9FkN
entities.urls: [{"start": 256, "end": 279, "url": "https://t.co/G3vu6U9FkN", "expanded_url": "https://www.digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHistory", "display_url": "digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHist\u2026", "images": [{"url": "https://pbs.twimg.com/news_img/1597322322679304192/pfUcrk5S?format=jpg&name=orig", "width": 412, "height": 600}, {"url": "https://pbs.twimg.com/news_img/1597322322679304192/pfUcrk5S?format=jpg&name=150x150", "width": 150, "height": 150}], "status": 200, "title": "LGB and/or T History - Digital Transgender Archive", "description": "Any line we might try to draw to separate lesbian/gay/bisexual history (LGB) from transgender history (trans) would be imprecise, blurry, and certainly not straight. Because of the incomplete archives we have, attempts to separate histories of sexuality and gender transgression often resort to pure guesswork. Worse, just trying to find that line forces us to consider all of history through two modern categories \u2013 gender and sexuality \u2013 making it harder to understand the very thing we are researching.", "unwound_url": "https://www.digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHistory"}]

The Centre\u2019s research innovates and intersects across a range of inter-connected cross-disciplinary projects, providing evidence focused on three key program areas \u2013 the Healthy Child, the Educated Child and the Connected Child. text: It is impossible to separate gay history from trans history, & attempts to do so inevitably collapse into bad scholarship. This has been a theme in my work for decades, and I'm honored that the Digital Transgender Archive invited me to write about it: https://t.co/G3vu6U9FkN
entities.urls: [{"start": 256, "end": 279, "url": "https://t.co/G3vu6U9FkN", "expanded_url": "https://www.digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHistory", "display_url": "digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHist\u2026", "images": [{"url": "https://pbs.twimg.com/news_img/1597322322679304192/pfUcrk5S?format=jpg&name=orig", "width": 412, "height": 600}, {"url": "https://pbs.twimg.com/news_img/1597322322679304192/pfUcrk5S?format=jpg&name=150x150", "width": 150, "height": 150}], "status": 200, "title": "LGB and/or T History - Digital Transgender Archive", "description": "Any line we might try to draw to separate lesbian/gay/bisexual history (LGB) from transgender history (trans) would be imprecise, blurry, and certainly not straight. Because of the incomplete archives we have, attempts to separate histories of sexuality and gender transgression often resort to pure guesswork. Worse, just trying to find that line forces us to consider all of history through two modern categories \u2013 gender and sexuality \u2013 making it harder to understand the very thing we are researching.", "unwound_url": "https://www.digitaltransgenderarchive.net/learn/LGBTHistory"}]

text: @Jacob_Labendz There’s a lot of wacky fodder out there!! Look up “Grindr Remembers” and “Yolocaust.” I’d recommend Shandler’s _Holocaust Memory in the Digital Age_ for scholarship.

text:
Evelyn was a migrant domestic worker for more than 30 years.

But today, thanks to a training scholarship that allowed her to acquire digital skills, she secured a decent job locally and fulfilled her longing to be with her family. 🤍
